eding strangers, keeping secrets-in an extraordinary time. For this, they are known as "Righteous Among the Nations of the World." The rescuers and survivors are from many countries in Europe-Italy, the Netherlands, Denmark, Norway, France, Bulgaria, Poland, Germany-and they tell their stories with simplicity and dignity. Each story is interwoven with old snapshots of rescuers and survivors, their homes, their hiding places, and the communities in which they lived. Noted author, teacher, and human rights activist, Elie Wiesel, helps us to ask: "what made these people different?" He points out how those who helped Jews during the Holocaust "changed history" by their actions. The Courage to Care reminds readers of the power of individual action. This compelling book is the companion volume to the award-winning film, The Courage to Care, and includes the personal narratives of the same persons in the film and many others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRighteous Gentiles in the Holocaust. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescuezFrancezLe Chambon-sur-Lignon. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescue. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBejski, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreznitz, Shlomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Irving, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalle, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAfee Brown, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyers, Sondra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRittner, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauvage, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiesel, Elie, econtribut